A study conducted by British doctors on middle-aged men revealed that shorter telomeres in white blood cells are linked to a higher risk of heart disease.
This genetic predisposition is more pronounced in women with a certain gene variant.
Additionally, gum disease has been associated with an increased risk of pancreatic cancer.
The study emphasizes the importance of early detection and personalized medicine to reduce the risk of cardiovascular diseases.
Furthermore, air pollution has been identified as a significant factor in increasing the risk of heart disease, particularly in postmenopausal women.
These findings highlight the need for targeted interventions and lifestyle modifications to prevent heart-related illnesses.
